","1183–1258":"1183–1258","1188–Female":"1188–Deceased","–1207":"–1207","1210–1261":"1210–1261","1158–Male":"1158–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","28 Oct 1258":"28 October 1258","1261":"1261","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","after 1207":"after 1207","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1188":"1188","about 1210":"about 1210","1207":"1207","Tankersley, Yorkshire, England":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, England","Tankerlsey Hall,Yorkshire,England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tankersley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Yorkshire and Lincolnshire):","habitational name from Tankersley in Yorkshire, named from the Old English personal name <i>Thancrēd</i> (genitive <i>Thancrēdes</i>) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. This surname has now died out in Britain.","occasional variant of <b>Donkersley</b>, itself a variant of   Dunkerley  , see   Dunkley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunkerley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Dunkley  ."]},{"name":"Tanksley","meanings":["Apparently a shortened form of   Tankersley  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":32,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":41,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Tankersley was born in 1183, in Tankersley, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Lord Dolphin de Tankersley, was 26 and his mother, Lady De Poitevin, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Galiena Poyntee. He died on 28 October 1258, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1183–28 Oct 1258":"1183–28. oktoober 1258","1183–1258":"1183–1258","1188–Female":"1188–Surnud","–1207":"–1207","1210–1261":"1210–1261","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","28 Oct 1258":"28. oktoober 1258","1261":"1261","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","after 1207":"pärast 1207","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1188